"""
MKT Context Commentary — Daniel chapters 9–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-daniel-9-11-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/daniel.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/daniel.json (MKT text)

Key historical decisions:
- Dan 9:1: Darius the Mede is most likely Gubaru (governor of Babylon under Cyrus) or
  an alternative name/title for Cyrus himself; 'first year' = 539 BCE.
- Dan 9:24-27 (70 weeks): Four major interpretive schools noted; historical anchoring
  of the decree candidates discussed without advocating a single school.
- Dan 11:2-20: Treated as Diadochi history (Ptolemies vs. Seleucids) — well-established
  scholarly consensus; identifications given for major figures.
- Dan 11:36-45: The historical/eschatological transition question is noted; the narrative
  shifts in vv.40-45 do not match Antiochus IV's historical death at Tabae (Persia).
- 'Ships of Kittim' (11:30) = Roman fleet / Roman legation of Popillius Laenas, 168 BCE.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DANIEL = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p><strong>Darius the Mede</strong> — one of the most debated figures in Daniel. No Median king of Babylon named Darius appears in extant cuneiform records; the city fell to Cyrus the Great of Persia in October 539 BCE. Proposed identifications include: (1) Gubaru, the Persian governor Cyrus appointed over Babylon, also known from tablets as "governor of Babylon and across the river"; (2) Cyaxares II, a figure in Xenophon\'s <em>Cyropaedia</em> not otherwise attested; (3) Cyrus himself, using a Median throne name. "Appointed king" (<em>humlak</em>, passive) — the passive construction in 9:1 (cf. 5:31) suggests someone elevated to a position rather than reigning by hereditary right, consistent with a governor or viceroy. The Median descent fits Gubaru\'s profile.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>Jeremiah\'s 70 years</strong> — Daniel is reading Jer 25:11-12 and 29:10, where YHWH promised 70 years of Babylonian dominion before restoration. With Babylon\'s fall in 539 BCE and Jeremiah\'s prophecy delivered ~605 BCE, the period was approaching its close. This is a remarkable scene: the prophet who receives new visions is also a careful reader of earlier Scripture, interpreting the present moment against the prior word of God. The act of discerning the "time of the end" through Scripture reading is a model of prophetic hermeneutics.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The penitential posture — <strong>sackcloth and ashes</strong> — was the standard mourning and supplication practice across the ANE. Sackcloth (<em>saq</em>) was coarse goat or camel hair cloth worn against the skin; ash (<em>epher</em>) was smeared on the face or sat in as a sign of grief and worthlessness. Fasting, sackcloth, and ashes together appear in Jonah 3:6 (Nineveh\'s repentance), Esther 4:1-3, and Neh 9:1 — each time as communal crisis response. Daniel turns his face (<em>panav</em>) toward "the Lord God" — a directional act matching the temple-oriented prayer of 1 Kgs 8:35, 48.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The prayer opens with the covenant-keeping formula: "great and awesome God, who keeps covenant and steadfast love (<em>chesed</em>) for those who love him and keep his commandments" — a direct echo of Deut 7:9 and Neh 9:32. This is the <em>berakhah</em> (blessing/address) form standard in Second Temple Jewish prayer. The appeal is grounded not in Israel\'s merit but in YHWH\'s prior self-commitment (<em>hesed</em>) to the covenant — a standard feature of biblical lament and confession prayers (Ezra 9:6-15; Neh 9).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The fivefold confession — "we have sinned (<em>chata\'nu</em>), acted wickedly (<em>avinu</em>), done evil (<em>hirsha\'nu</em>), rebelled (<em>maradnu</em>), and turned aside (<em>sarnu</em>)" — exhausts Hebrew vocabulary for covenant violation. The accumulation is intentional: each term covers a different register of the transgression, from moral failure to willful rebellion. This confessional stacking pattern appears also in Solomon\'s temple prayer (1 Kgs 8:47) and Lev 26:40.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The prophetic office in its social range: YHWH\'s prophets spoke to "our kings, our princes, our ancestors, and all the people of the land" — a complete vertical cross-section of Israelite society. The point is that no group can claim ignorance; the message was delivered at every level of the social hierarchy. The failure was not lack of information but refusal to hear — <em>lo shamanu</em> (we did not listen/obey).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"To you, O Lord, belongs righteousness (<em>tsedaqah</em>)" while "to us belongs shame (<em>boshet panim</em>)" — the rhetorical contrast of divine righteousness and human shame structures the entire prayer. "Open shame" (<em>boshet panim</em>, lit. "shame of face") is public disgrace in an honor-shame culture; the exile was experienced as a cosmic humiliation — proof of YHWH\'s rejection. The prayer reframes this: the shame belongs to Israel, not to God; YHWH\'s righteousness is vindicated by the very disaster that Israel interpreted as God\'s absence.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The shame of exile extends to every social stratum — "kings, princes, and ancestors" — emphasizing that the covenant failure was not one generation\'s but the cumulative defection of Israel\'s entire governing and priestly class. The prayer is a liturgical act of taking corporate responsibility before YHWH rather than deflecting blame onto circumstances or enemies.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Mercy and forgiveness (<em>rachamim u-selichot</em>)" — the two divine attributes appealed to in contrast with Israel\'s rebellion. <em>Selichot</em> (plural of <em>selichah</em>) is the Jewish liturgical term for forgiveness prayers; the plural form implies abundance of forgiveness available. This is the sole note of hope in the litany of confession: the very covenant God whose commandments were broken is the God characterized by abundant forgiveness (Ps 130:4, 7-8).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The formula "we have not obeyed the voice (<em>qol</em>) of YHWH our God" echoes Deut 8:20; 28:1-2, 15 — the covenantal listen-obey motif (<em>shama\' be-qol</em>) that structures Deuteronomy throughout. The laws given "through his servants the prophets" frames the prophetic office as a communication of the Mosaic covenant to successive generations, not as innovation.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>The Deuteronomic curse</strong> — "the curse and sworn judgment written in the Torah of Moses" (Deut 27-28, 30:1-10; Lev 26:14-45). Deuteronomy 28 specifically predicts exile, siege, starvation, and dispersal among the nations as consequences of covenant breaking. Daniel interprets the Babylonian exile explicitly as the fulfillment of Deuteronomic covenant curses — not random political catastrophe but precisely the covenant sanctions YHWH warned of through Moses.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"No disaster like what was done to Jerusalem" — the comparative superlative formula expressing incomparable catastrophe (cf. Joel 2:2; Dan 12:1). The destruction of Jerusalem and the temple in 587/6 BCE by Nebuchadnezzar included the death of tens of thousands, the burning of the temple (which had stood for four centuries), the deportation of the leadership class, and the termination of Davidic monarchy. From a covenantal standpoint, it was the collapse of every institutional expression of God\'s covenant with Israel.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"We have not sought the favor of YHWH (<em>challot et-penei YHWH</em>)" — the idiom literally means "to make smooth/sweet the face of YHWH," i.e., to seek divine favor through prayer and righteous action. Even after the disaster, Israel did not turn to repentance. The verse is an indictment of the exile community itself: being in exile did not automatically produce the repentance that would restore the covenant relationship.</p>',
    "14": '<p>YHWH "watched for the right moment to bring the disaster" (<em>shaqqad YHWH al-ha-ra\'ah</em>) — the same verb (<em>shaqad</em>, to be awake/watching) used in Jer 1:12 for God watching over his word to perform it. Far from being absent or defeated, YHWH was actively providential in the catastrophe; the exile was not the triumph of Babylon\'s gods but the judicial act of Israel\'s own God executing covenant sanction.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Exodus invocation — "who brought your people out of Egypt with a mighty hand and won for yourself renown" — grounds the prayer in Israel\'s foundational redemptive experience. The argument is: you delivered once, therefore deliver again. The Exodus was the paradigm event that established YHWH\'s identity as Israel\'s redeemer; every subsequent prayer for national deliverance appeals to it (Pss 77, 78, 105-106; Neh 9:9-11).</p>',
    "16": '<p>Jerusalem is identified as "your city" and the surrounding land as "your holy mountain" — the covenant geography of divine ownership. The prayer appeals to YHWH\'s reputation among the nations: the city\'s desolation has made Israel "a reproach (<em>cherpah</em>) to all around us," which reflects back on YHWH\'s name. This is the classic Mosaic intercession motif (Num 14:13-16; Exod 32:11-12): spare Israel for the sake of your own name among the nations.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The prayer shifts to petitions: "hear," "let your face shine (<em>ha\'er panekha</em>) on your desolate sanctuary." The "shining face" language is from the Aaronic benediction (Num 6:25): YHWH\'s face shining on the sanctuary would signal restored favor and divine presence returning to the empty temple. The sanctuary is destroyed; what Daniel prays for is not merely its reconstruction but the return of YHWH\'s presence to dwell there again.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Not because of our righteous deeds but because of your great mercy (<em>rachamim</em>)" — the prayer explicitly disclaims merit-based pleading. The appeal is entirely to divine character, not human achievement. This is the theological position of Ezra 9:13-15 and Neh 9:33 as well: the restoration, when it comes, will demonstrate YHWH\'s grace, not Israel\'s worthiness.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The triple imperative — "O Lord, hear! O Lord, forgive! O Lord, listen and act!" — is the liturgical climax of the prayer. The urgency is expressed by the double call to listening (<em>shema\'</em> / <em>haqshivah</em>) and the explicit "do not delay." The final motivation: "for your own sake, O my God" — the restoration is not only for Israel\'s benefit but for YHWH\'s own honor.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The phrase "while I was still speaking" — Gabriel\'s arrival is immediate, before the prayer concludes. The narrative detail that Daniel was confessing "the sin of my people Israel" and presenting the plea "before YHWH my God, for his holy mountain" establishes that the prayer was genuinely intercession, not merely personal petition. The response comes during prayer — a pattern also in Isa 65:24 ("before they call I will answer").</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>Gabriel</strong> — one of only two angels named in the canonical OT (the other being Michael). In Second Temple Jewish angelology (1 Enoch, Tobit), Gabriel was one of four archangels. His earlier appearance to Daniel was in ch. 8 (the vision of the ram and goat). <em>Yu\'aph bi-yephia\'</em> — translated "swift flight" or "caused to fly in exhaustion/weariness"; the Aramaic is ambiguous. The "evening sacrifice" (<em>minchah ha-erev</em>) was offered at approximately 3 PM — giving a time anchor for the revelation.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Gabriel\'s explicit purpose is "to give you insight (<em>haskel</em>) and understanding (<em>binah</em>)" — the same epistemic vocabulary of ch. 1. The angel\'s function is not to replace Daniel\'s study of Scripture (v.2) but to illuminate what his study of Jeremiah had opened up. Revelation builds on and interprets prior Scripture rather than superseding it.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>Highly esteemed / greatly beloved</strong> — <em>chamudot</em> (lit. "precious things" / "delights"), translated variously as "greatly beloved," "highly esteemed," or "treasure." The term appears again in 10:11 and 10:19, becoming Daniel\'s characteristic divine epithet. It implies both personal affection and covenantal standing before God. "A word went out" at the beginning of his prayer — the phrase stresses instantaneous divine responsiveness, undermining any sense that prayer must overcome divine reluctance.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>Seventy weeks</strong> (<em>shivim shavuim</em>, 70 sevens = 490 years) — the heptad structure extends Jeremiah\'s 70 years into a sabbatical framework drawn from the Jubilee calendar (Lev 25:8). Six purposes are listed for the 70 weeks: (1) to finish/restrain the transgression; (2) to put an end to sins; (3) to atone for iniquity; (4) to bring in everlasting righteousness; (5) to seal up vision and prophecy; (6) to anoint a most holy place/one. The interpretive schools differ significantly: the historical school sees fulfillment in the Maccabean period (Antiochus IV and the rededication of 164 BCE); the prophetic school reads it as pointing to Christ\'s first and second coming; the symbolic school treats it as non-calendar theological statement; combined approaches find both a near and far fulfillment.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>The decree to restore and rebuild Jerusalem</strong> — four candidates are debated: (1) Cyrus\'s decree, 538 BCE (Ezra 1:1-4); (2) Darius I\'s confirmation decree, 519 BCE (Ezra 6:1-12); (3) Artaxerxes I\'s decree to Ezra, 457 BCE (Ezra 7:12-26); (4) Artaxerxes I\'s authorization to Nehemiah, 445 BCE (Neh 2:1-8). Working from 445 BCE with prophetic years of 360 days, 69 weeks (483 years) brings one to approximately 32-33 CE — a calculation made famous by Sir Robert Anderson in <em>The Coming Prince</em> (1895). The phrase "Anointed One, the prince (<em>mashiach nagid</em>)" — both terms are royal/priestly titles; <em>mashiach</em> simply means "anointed one" and does not by itself specify messianic fulfillment in the later theological sense.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>Cut off and have nothing</strong> (<em>yikaret ve-eyn lo</em>) — "cut off" is the covenantal excision term (Lev 7:20-21), but here applied to the Anointed One himself. The passive construction ("have nothing" or "have no one for him") may indicate either rejection or sacrificial death without a following generation. <strong>The people of the prince to come</strong> destroying city and sanctuary — if "the prince" of v.26 differs from "the Anointed One" of v.25, then this refers to a future destructive ruler whose people (army) destroys Jerusalem: this is traditionally identified with the Roman destruction of 70 CE (Titus). The "flood" (<em>shiteph</em>) metaphor for irresistible military conquest appears also in Isa 8:8 and Nah 1:8.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The final week: the "he" who makes a covenant with many is grammatically ambiguous — either the "prince who is to come" (v.26) or possibly the Anointed One. The "middle of the week" cessation of sacrifice and the "abomination that desolates" (<em>shiqquts meshomem</em>) — this phrase is cited directly by Jesus (Matt 24:15) as pointing to a future event, suggesting that whatever its initial fulfillment, it retains future referent. In the Maccabean reading, Antiochus IV\'s altar to Zeus in 167 BCE fulfills this; in the prophetic reading, it points to a future eschatological desecration. The "appointed end (<em>kalah ve-necheratsat</em>) will be poured out on the desolator" — whatever the agent, its termination is divinely decreed.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p><strong>Third year of Cyrus</strong> = 536 BCE. Daniel has served at court since 605 BCE — approximately 70 years of public service. He would be in his 80s by this point. The message is described as "true" (<em>emet</em>) and concerning a "great conflict (<em>tzava gadol</em>)" — the phrase implies extended warfare or tribulation ahead. The explicit authentication ("the vision was true and it concerned a great conflict") frames what follows as a reliable disclosure of what is about to unfold in world history.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The three-week mourning fast (21 days) frames the vision temporally. The first month of the year in the Jewish calendar is Nisan (March-April); a three-week fast beginning at the new month would overlap entirely with Passover (Nisan 14-21). The fact that Daniel maintained his mourning through Passover — the great feast of redemption — intensifies the gravity of his concern for his people. He was likely distressed about the state of the return from exile and the obstacles to rebuilding the temple (cf. Ezra 1-3).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The partial nature of the fast — "no choice food, no meat or wine, no lotions" — resembles mourning practice rather than the full fast of Yom Kippur (no food or water). The prohibition on oil/lotion was standard in mourning contexts (2 Sam 12:20 — David resumed anointing himself after his son\'s death; Ruth 3:3 — Ruth anoints herself as a sign of restored relationship). This extended partial fast signals protracted intercessory grief, not a brief liturgical act.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The <strong>Tigris</strong> (<em>Hiddekel</em>) — one of the four rivers of Eden (Gen 2:14), now the great river of the Assyrian/Babylonian heartland. Daniel\'s position on its bank echoes Ezekiel\'s visionary reception by the Chebar canal (Ezek 1:1, 3). The use of the ancient Eden-associated name links the revelation site to primordial creation geography — the visions Daniel receives concern ultimate reality.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The <strong>man clothed in linen</strong> (<em>levush badim</em>) — linen was the material of priestly garments (Lev 16:4; Ezek 9:2). The figure\'s clothing marks him as belonging to the heavenly court. <strong>Fine gold from Uphaz</strong> — Uphaz is of uncertain location; some identify it with Ophir (Job 28:16; 1 Kgs 9:28), the source of the finest gold, suggesting superlative quality rather than a specific geography. The gold belt signals royal authority combined with priestly purity.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theophanic description — body like chrysolite (<em>tarshish</em>), face like lightning (<em>baraq</em>), eyes like flaming torches, arms and feet like burnished bronze (<em>nachoshet qalal</em>), voice like a multitude — is the most elaborate angelic/divine description in Daniel, closely paralleling Ezekiel\'s <em>kavod</em> vision (Ezek 1:26-28) and John\'s vision of the risen Christ (Rev 1:12-16). Whether this figure is angelic (Gabriel) or a divine appearance is debated; the similarity to Ezekiel\'s divine throne vision and Rev 1\'s Christ-figure suggests the description draws on the same heavenly archetype.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The pattern of Daniel alone seeing the vision while companions are overwhelmed with unexplained terror replicates the Sinai theophany pattern (Exod 19-20, where only Moses ascends; the people are terrified and flee) and Paul\'s Damascus road encounter (Acts 9:7, where companions heard but did not see). The terror experienced by those who do not see is more than psychological reaction — it is a response to genuine supernatural presence.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Daniel\'s physical response — strength failing, face going deadly pale — is the standard theophanic collapse pattern: Isaiah (Isa 6:5, "I am undone"), Ezekiel (Ezek 1:28, falling face down), John at Patmos (Rev 1:17, falling as though dead). The approach of unmediated divine glory overwhelms human constitution; Daniel\'s physical extremity validates the reality and intensity of what he is experiencing.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Deep sleep (<em>tardemah</em>) — the same word used for Adam\'s sleep before Eve\'s creation (Gen 2:21) and Abraham\'s sleep during the covenant-cutting ceremony (Gen 15:12). In biblical usage, <em>tardemah</em> marks a threshold between ordinary consciousness and divinely induced receptivity — the sleeper is not self-willed but passive before the divine act. Face to the ground is the prostration posture before divine majesty.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The touch (<em>naga\'</em>) that sets Daniel "trembling on his hands and knees" is an act of commission — the same type of enabling touch appears in Isaiah\'s coal-to-lips (Isa 6:7) and Jeremiah\'s hand to mouth (Jer 1:9). The movement from complete prostration to hands-and-knees is a staged restoration: first partial rising, then standing (v.11), then receiving strength to stand fully (v.19).</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Highly esteemed" (<em>ish chamudot</em>) — see note on 9:23. The commission formula "consider carefully (<em>hitsoneyn</em>) the words I speak to you, and stand upright (<em>amad</em>)" echoes the prophetic commissioning of Ezekiel (Ezek 2:1-2, "stand on your feet"). The act of receiving the divine word requires a posture of attentive standing — not prostration, not ease, but alert readiness.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Since the first day you set your heart" — the divine response was immediate from Day 1 of Daniel\'s prayer. The 21-day delay was not because prayer was unheard but because of spiritual conflict. This is one of the most explicit biblical passages about the relationship between intercessory prayer and angelic warfare: prayer activates divine response; the delay in visible answer does not indicate unanswered prayer but ongoing battle in the heavenly realm.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Prince of the Persian kingdom</strong> — the concept of national celestial guardians (patron angels of nations) is rooted in Deut 32:8 LXX / Dead Sea Scrolls fragment (4QDeut<sup>j</sup>): "when the Most High gave the nations their inheritance, he separated the sons of man; he set the boundaries of the peoples according to the number of the sons of God." The MT\'s "sons of Israel" is a later harmonizing variant; the original text indicates that nations have heavenly patron-beings over them. Daniel 10 dramatizes this theology: the political opposition of Persia to Jewish restoration has a heavenly correlate in the "prince of Persia" resisting the angelic messenger. <strong>Michael</strong>, described as "one of the chief princes," is Israel\'s patron angel (12:1; Rev 12:7).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"What will happen to your people in the latter days (<em>acharit ha-yamim</em>)" — the same eschatological formula from Deut 4:30 (in your distress in the latter days); Num 24:14 (Balaam\'s final oracle); and consistently in the prophets. The phrase spans the range from near historical fulfillment to ultimate eschatological consummation; Daniel\'s visions operate simultaneously on both levels.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The messenger\'s words about cosmic conflict and the future of Daniel\'s people leave Daniel silenced — "I looked down at the ground and could not speak." The weight of what is disclosed overwhelms the capacity for response. This muteness before revelation is a recurring motif: Zechariah (Luke 1:20), Isaiah before the seraphim (Isa 6:5). The silence is not irreverence but the appropriate human response to unbearable gravity.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"One who appeared to be a man" (possibly a second angelic figure, or the same messenger) touches Daniel\'s lips — the lips being the organ of speech, the touch restores the capacity for response. The lip-touch parallels the coal to Isaiah\'s lips (Isa 6:7) and YHWH\'s hand to Jeremiah\'s mouth (Jer 1:9) — each a commissioning act that enables the prophet to speak what he could not otherwise utter.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"How can I, your servant, speak with you, my lord? My strength is gone and I can hardly breathe" — the physical language of spiritual depletion: <em>neshamah</em> (breath) barely remaining. In Hebrew anthropology, breath is life (Gen 2:7); its near-absence signals near-death. The double confession of weakness (<em>koach</em>) — first exhaustion, then breathlessness — is the human side of the theophanic encounter, expressing what direct proximity to the divine costs.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The messenger touches Daniel a second time, giving strength (<em>chizzeqani</em>, from H2388 <em>chazaq</em>, to strengthen) — the same root as Hezekiah\'s name (YHWH strengthens). The repeated acts of touch, strengthening, and commission build to the full restoration that enables Daniel to receive the revelation of chs. 11-12. Divine commissioning always includes the provision of what is required to fulfill the commission.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"O man highly esteemed (<em>ish chamudot</em>), do not be afraid. Peace (<em>shalom</em>). Be strong, be strong." — The triple greeting form — address by title, peace-declaration, double imperative of strength — is the most elaborate angelic commission formula in Daniel. "When he spoke to me, I was strengthened" — the word itself carries the strength it commands, a feature of the divine word throughout the OT (Ps 29; Isa 55:10-11).</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Fight against the prince of Persia" — the angelic messenger will return to the cosmic conflict after delivering the revelation. Then the "prince of Greece (<em>sar Yavan</em>)" will come — anticipating the shift from Persian to Greek world empire that ch. 11 will trace in detail. The succession of heavenly "princes" maps directly onto the political succession of world empires: Persia → Greece → Rome. What follows in ch. 11 is the earthly narrative of what these heavenly battles determine.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>Book of Truth</strong> (<em>sefer emet</em>) — the heavenly record of what will unfold, a document written before the events occur. This concept of the heavenly book appears also in Ps 139:16 (all Daniel\'s days were written in the book before one came to be), Exod 32:32-33 (the book of the living), and Rev 5:1 (the sealed scroll). <strong>Michael, your prince</strong> — Israel has its own celestial patron, and he fights alongside the angelic messenger. The disclosure of this cosmic framework is itself protective: Daniel knows that despite earthly appearances, Israel is not abandoned in the heavenly court.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>The angelic narrator (the messenger from ch. 10) reports supporting Darius the Mede in his first year — the cosmic guardians of empires shape political stability. The verse bridges chs. 10-11 and confirms the continuity of the angelic narrator across both chapters. This reinforces that the detailed prediction of chs. 11-12 comes from the heavenly realm, not human political analysis.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>Three more Persian kings, then a fourth</strong> — from the narrator\'s standpoint (Cyrus\'s third year, 536 BCE), three successors of Cyrus followed: Cambyses II (530-522 BCE), Smerdis/Bardiya (522 BCE, briefly), and Darius I Hystaspes (522-486 BCE). The fourth king, "far richer than all the others, who will stir up all against Greece," is Xerxes I (486-465 BCE) — the Ahasuerus of Esther, who launched the massive Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BCE immortalized at Thermopylae and Salamis. The description "with all his wealth" matches Herodotus\'s account of Xerxes\'s vast mobilization.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>A powerful king who will do as he pleases</strong> — Alexander the Great (356-323 BCE), who conquered the Persian Empire in a decade of campaigning (334-323 BCE). The description "do as he pleases (<em>ya\'aseh kirtso\'no</em>)" is a consistent formula for self-willed absolute power in Daniel (11:3, 16, 36; cf. 8:4), applied here to Alexander and later to the eschatological figure of 11:36.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Kingdom shattered and broken up toward the four winds</strong> — Alexander died in Babylon in June 323 BCE at age 32 without a legitimate heir (Roxane\'s son Alexander IV was posthumous). His empire was divided by the Diadochi (successors): primarily into the Ptolemaic kingdom (Egypt) and the Seleucid kingdom (Syria/Mesopotamia), with Macedon and Thrace going to others. The "four winds" division matches the four major successor kingdoms. "Not to his posterity" — the phrase specifically notes that his legitimate heirs (his half-brother Arrhidaeus, murdered 317 BCE, and son Alexander IV, murdered 310 BCE) did not retain power.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>King of the south</strong> = Ptolemy I Soter (305-285 BCE), who established the Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt. <strong>One of his commanders who will become greater</strong> = Seleucus I Nicator — Seleucus initially fled to Egypt after Antigonus drove him out of Babylon (316 BCE) and served under Ptolemy before recovering Babylon in 312 BCE and establishing the Seleucid empire, which at its height exceeded Ptolemy\'s territory.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>An alliance through the king\'s daughter</strong> — ca. 252 BCE, Ptolemy II Philadelphus gave his daughter Berenice in marriage to Antiochus II Theos of the Seleucid kingdom, on the condition that Antiochus divorce his first wife Laodice. When Ptolemy II died, Antiochus took Laodice back, who then had Antiochus II poisoned, Berenice and her son killed, and placed her own son Seleucus II on the throne. This episode fulfilled the detail that "she will not retain her position of authority" — Berenice and her Egyptian entourage came to nothing.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>One from her family line will arise</strong> = Berenice\'s brother Ptolemy III Euergetes (246-221 BCE), who invaded the Seleucid kingdom in the "Laodicean War" (246-241 BCE) in revenge for his sister\'s murder. He reached deep into Syria and Mesopotamia, plundering Seleucia-on-the-Tigris. "Enter the fortress (<em>ma\'oz</em>) of the king of the north" — he captured the Seleucid capital Seleucia-on-the-Tigris and carried off enormous booty.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Ptolemy III returned to Egypt with "their gods, their metal images, and precious articles of silver and gold" — Polybius and other Greek sources confirm that he returned cult images that Cambyses had taken from Egypt three centuries earlier, making him enormously popular with the Egyptian priesthood (hence his title "Euergetes," benefactor). He survived longer than the king of the north (Seleucus II), as predicted.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Seleucus II\'s counterattack into Egypt (ca. 240 BCE) failed and he "retreated to his own country" — an exact correspondence to the text. The third Syrian War ended with no Seleucid gains; Seleucus II subsequently faced revolts in Asia Minor and died on campaign ca. 226 BCE.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>His sons</strong> = Seleucus III (226-223 BCE) and Antiochus III "the Great" (223-187 BCE). Seleucus III campaigned but was assassinated; Antiochus III pursued the reconquest of Palestine and Coele-Syria. "Sweep forward like a flood" — Antiochus III\'s early campaigns recovered much Seleucid territory. "Will wage war as far as his fortress" — he pressed to the borders of Egypt.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Battle of Raphia</strong> (217 BCE) — Ptolemy IV Philopator marched out "furious" against Antiochus III\'s invasion. The Battle of Raphia (modern Rafah, Gaza-Egypt border) was a decisive Ptolemaic victory; ancient sources (Polybius 5.79-86) record Ptolemy\'s army of 70,000 infantry, 5,000 cavalry, and 73 elephants defeating Antiochus\'s slightly larger force. "The large army will be given into his hand" — Ptolemy IV won, as predicted.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Ptolemy IV\'s failure after Raphia — he became "arrogant" and did not press the victory to consolidate control. Contemporary sources describe his debauchery and mismanagement; he celebrated at Alexandria rather than annexing Syria. According to 3 Maccabees (historically questionable but reflecting the tradition), he sacrilegiously tried to enter the Jerusalem temple\'s inner precincts, was struck unconscious, and returned to Egypt without completing his advantage — consistent with "yet he will not maintain his ascendancy."</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Antiochus III returns with a larger army</strong> — after Raphia (217 BCE), Antiochus III spent the next decade reconquering the eastern satrapies of the empire (the "Anabasis," 212-205 BCE), giving himself the epithet "the Great." With Ptolemy IV dead (204 BCE) and the child Ptolemy V on the throne, Antiochus allied with Philip V of Macedon and launched his reconquest of Coele-Syria/Palestine (203-198 BCE).</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Violent men among your own people</strong> — the Hellenizing Jews who supported Antiochus III\'s takeover of Palestine from the Ptolemies in hopes of political advantage. Josephus (<em>Antiquities</em> 12.3.3) records that some Jews aided Antiochus III. "They will rebel against the vision" — their collaboration with imperial power ultimately failed to fulfill their ambitions; the Hellenizing project eventually produced the Maccabean crisis rather than Jewish privilege.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>Capture of the well-fortified city</strong> — traditionally identified as Sidon (Polybius 16.18-19), which Antiochus III besieged and captured from the Ptolemaic general Scopas in 198 BCE. The "choice troops of the south" who could not resist = the Ptolemaic forces under Scopas. Antiochus III\'s victory at Panion (near modern Banias/Caesarea Philippi, 198 BCE) effectively ended Ptolemaic control of Palestine.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>The Beautiful Land</strong> (<em>eretz ha-tzevi</em>) — the standard Daniel term for the Holy Land (cf. 8:9, 11:41). Antiochus III "established himself" in Judea ca. 198 BCE and issued decrees favorable to the Jews (Josephus, <em>Antiquities</em> 12.3.3-4), granting tax relief and supporting the temple cult — a stark contrast to what his son Antiochus IV would do 30 years later. "All of it in his power to destroy" — he had unchallenged control over the Beautiful Land.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>His daughter to the king of the south</strong> — Antiochus III gave his daughter Cleopatra I as wife to the young Ptolemy V (ca. 196 BCE) as part of the Peace of Lysimacheia, retaining nominal sovereignty over Coele-Syria. His hope that she would act as a Seleucid intelligence asset backfired — "but his plan will not succeed, nor will it help him," as Cleopatra sided with her husband Ptolemy V and even supported Rome against her own father. The scheme to "undermine the realm of Egypt through her" failed completely.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>Turn his attention to the coastlands</strong> — after consolidating his eastern and Palestinian gains, Antiochus III turned westward, campaigning in Asia Minor and even landing in Greece (192 BCE). <strong>A commander will put an end to his insolence</strong> = the Roman general Lucius Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus (brother of Scipio Africanus), who defeated Antiochus III decisively at the Battle of Magnesia in Lydia (190 BCE). The Romans were not yet a named power in Daniel\'s framework; they appear obliquely here and more directly in 11:30 ("ships of Kittim").</p>',
    "19": '<p>After Magnesia, Antiochus III was forced to surrender his fleet, his war elephants, and territory west of the Taurus mountains (Treaty of Apamea, 188 BCE). He returned east ("fortresses of his own country") and was killed at Elymais in Persia (187 BCE) while trying to plunder the temple of Bel at Elymais to pay the Roman war indemnity. "He will stumble and fall, to be seen no more" — the most powerful Seleucid ruler died ignominiously attempting temple robbery.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>A tax collector through the prestigious part of the kingdom</strong> = Seleucus IV Philopator (187-175 BCE), who sent his minister Heliodorus to plunder the Jerusalem temple treasury to raise Roman tribute money (2 Macc 3:1-40). Heliodorus was supernaturally prevented (the tradition in 2 Macc 3 of a heavenly horseman). Seleucus IV was subsequently poisoned by Heliodorus himself ("destroyed, yet not in anger or in battle") in 175 BCE.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>A contemptible person</strong> — Antiochus IV Epiphanes (175-164 BCE), younger son of Antiochus III. He was not the legitimate heir; Seleucus IV\'s son Demetrius was the rightful heir (then held hostage in Rome). Antiochus seized power through flattery (<em>chalaqalot</em>) of the Seleucid nobility and allies, not by traditional succession. He gave himself the title <em>Epiphanes</em> (God Manifest); opponents called him <em>Epimanes</em> (the Mad One). His treatment of the Jerusalem high priesthood (purchasing the office for the highest bidder — Jason replacing Onias III in 175 BCE, then Menelaus replacing Jason in 172 BCE) was the first major act of covenant desecration in his reign.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>Prince of the covenant will be shattered</strong> — widely identified as Onias III, the last legitimate high priest, who was deposed and ultimately murdered ca. 171 BCE (2 Macc 4:33-38). The high priest was the "prince of the covenant" in the sense that he presided over Israel\'s covenant worship; his removal and murder marked the end of the legitimate Zadokite high priesthood. An "overwhelming army" was swept away by Antiochus IV\'s military campaigns in Egypt.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Antiochus IV came to power with "only a small force" — he initially ruled with limited military resources, using political cunning before building up strength. His deceit and intrigue against both the Seleucid nobility and the Jewish leadership are well-documented in 1-2 Maccabees. The "alliance" may refer to his initial cooperative relationship with Ptolemy VI Philometor before the conflict of 170-168 BCE.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Without warning he will invade the most productive areas" — Antiochus IV\'s practice of sudden, unexpected invasion, distributing plunder to buy loyalty, was noted by ancient writers. The phrase "accomplish what his ancestors never did" — his willingness to desecrate temples (ultimately the Jerusalem temple) and break all customary boundaries went beyond even his predecessors. "For a time" (<em>ad et</em>) — the temporal limit is built into the prediction; his power has a divinely appointed terminus.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>First Egyptian campaign</strong> (170-169 BCE) — Antiochus IV invaded Egypt using Ptolemy VI Philometor\'s advisors\' treachery as a pretext (they had actually incited the conflict). He defeated the Egyptian army near Pelusium and occupied much of Egypt, including Memphis, leaving Ptolemy VI as a puppet. The "large army raised against him" refers to the Ptolemaic forces that were outmaneuvered and defeated.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Ptolemy VI was undermined by those of "his own table" — his advisors and inner court who proved disloyal or incompetent. The defeat of the Egyptian army is confirmed by Polybius and Livy. Antiochus IV effectively controlled Egypt except for Alexandria, which held out behind the Ptolemaic navy.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The famous meeting of Antiochus IV and Ptolemy VI at which "both kings will tell lies to each other" — Polybius (28.21) describes diplomatic negotiations between the two at Memphis that both knew to be insincere. Ptolemy VI secretly sought Roman intervention while appearing to cooperate with Antiochus; Antiochus maintained the pretense of acting as Ptolemy VI\'s protector while pursuing his own annexation. "But to no avail" — neither king achieved his objective at this meeting.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>Returning through Judea</strong> — on his return from Egypt (169 BCE), Antiochus IV plundered the Jerusalem temple, taking "the golden altar, the lampstand, and all its vessels" (1 Macc 1:21-24). This was the first major desecration of the temple. "His heart set against the holy covenant" — the temple plunder was not incidental but reflected ideological hostility to the covenant community. He "returned to his own country" before the climactic desecration of 167 BCE.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>Second Egyptian campaign</strong> (168 BCE) — Antiochus IV invaded Egypt again, this time with greater force, intending permanent annexation. However, "this time the outcome will be different from what it was before" — Rome was now directly involved.</p>',
    "30": '<p><strong>Ships of Kittim</strong> — in the OT, Kittim originally referred to Cyprus (Num 24:24; Isa 23:1), but by the second century BCE it was used for Rome in Jewish texts (the Dead Sea Scrolls War Scroll consistently uses "Kittim" for Rome). This verse describes the famous confrontation of 168 BCE at Alexandria: the Roman senator Gaius Popillius Laenas presented Antiochus IV with the Senate\'s ultimatum to withdraw from Egypt. When Antiochus asked for time to consider, Popillius drew a circle in the sand around Antiochus and demanded an answer before he stepped out of it. Antiochus submitted, withdrawing from Egypt entirely. "He will turn back and vent his fury against the holy covenant" — the humiliation at Rome\'s hands redirected his aggression toward Judea.</p>',
    "31": '<p><strong>The abomination of desolation</strong> — December 167 BCE: Antiochus IV\'s forces (under his general Apollonius according to 1 Macc 1:29-35) garrisoned Jerusalem, abolished the <em>tamid</em> (daily morning and evening sacrifice), and erected an altar to Olympian Zeus on the altar of burnt offering. 1 Macc 1:54 calls this the "abomination of desolation"; 2 Macc 6:2 adds that the temple was renamed the sanctuary of Zeus Olympios. Pigs were sacrificed on the altar. This event directly triggered the Maccabean revolt (1 Macc 2:1-28). Jesus cites this verse explicitly in Matt 24:15, indicating it has a further eschatological referent beyond Antiochus IV.</p>',
    "32": '<p><strong>Corrupt those who violate the covenant</strong> — the Hellenizing Jews (the Tobiads, the high priests Jason and Menelaus) who collaborated with Antiochus IV and adopted Greek customs, abandoning circumcision and the Torah (1 Macc 1:11-15). <strong>People who know their God will stand firm</strong> — the Hasidim ("pious ones"), a movement of Torah-faithful Jews who formed the core of the Maccabean resistance. The Hasidim are the probable ancestors of both the Pharisees and the Essenes (Dead Sea Scrolls community).</p>',
    "33": '<p><strong>The wise will instruct many</strong> (<em>maskilei am yavinu le-rabbim</em>) — the teachers of the covenant community. The catalogue of suffering — sword, burning, captivity, plunder — corresponds directly to the persecution under Antiochus IV documented in 1-2 Maccabees: thousands were killed, families were slaughtered for observing the Sabbath or circumcising sons (1 Macc 1:60-64). The "little help" may refer to the Maccabean revolt under Mattathias and his sons — effective but ultimately limited; it purified the temple but did not bring the eschatological kingdom.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Many who join them will do so insincerely" (<em>venilavim alehem bachalaqlot</em>) — in every revival or movement of faithfulness, opportunists join for advantage rather than conviction. The Maccabean movement attracted both the deeply faithful and those who joined for political or material reasons. The acknowledgment that the community of resistance is not pure does not invalidate the movement; God works through the mixed community of the partially faithful.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The stumbling of the wise "to refine, purify, and cleanse" them (<em>labreram u-lalbenim u-latsaraph</em>) — the same triple metallurgical language as Dan 12:10. The suffering of the faithful is not meaningless but has a refining purpose. "Until the time of the end (<em>ad et qetz</em>)" — this phrase introduces an eschatological horizon that some interpreters see as signaling a transition from the Maccabean historical period to a future fulfillment in vv.36-45.</p>',
    "36": '<p><strong>A transition point</strong> — most scholars note that beginning here, the description does not easily map onto the historical career of Antiochus IV. Antiochus IV died at Tabae in Persia (164 BCE) while besieged at Elymais, having failed to plunder a temple; he died "in anger and in battle" in one sense, but not "between the sea and the holy mountain" (v.45) as predicted. Many interpreters therefore see a transition at v.36 to an eschatological figure — either a future Antichrist figure (Christian/Jewish eschatological tradition) or a symbolic composite. The description "exalting himself above every god, speaking unheard-of things against the God of gods" has parallels in 2 Thess 2:4 and Rev 13:5-6.</p>',
    "37": '<p><strong>No regard for the gods of his ancestors or for the one desired by women</strong> — "gods of his ancestors" is debated: if read of Antiochus IV, it may refer to his neglect of traditional Seleucid gods in favor of Zeus Olympios. "The one desired by women" (<em>chemdat nashim</em>) — variously interpreted as Tammuz/Adonis (a dying-and-rising deity whose cult was practiced by women; cf. Ezek 8:14) or as a general reference to family or conjugal affection. The verse describes comprehensive rejection of all prior religious and relational loyalties.</p>',
    "38": '<p><strong>God of fortresses</strong> (<em>Elohei ma\'oz</em>) — the deity Antiochus IV honored above all others. In Roman tradition, Antiochus IV was known for his devotion to Jupiter Capitolinus (Zeus Olympios), whom he identified with his own divine manifestation (<em>Epiphanes</em>). The consistent identification with military fortress-power fits his use of military force as the instrument of his will and his cult.</p>',
    "39": '<p>Distributing land as reward to those who "acknowledge" the foreign god — Antiochus IV\'s practice of giving land grants to loyal supporters who adopted Hellenistic cult practices. This was a systematic program of using land redistribution to incentivize religious apostasy among the Jewish elite (cf. 1 Macc 2:18, where Mattathias is offered such incentives).</p>',
    "40": '<p><strong>At the time of the end</strong> (<em>be-et qetz</em>) — the phrase marks the eschatological timeframe. Whether this describes Antiochus IV\'s final campaigns or a future eschatological figure, the geography is clear: a conflict between the "king of the south" and the "king of the north" that reaches the Holy Land. If read of Antiochus IV, it anticipates a final Egyptian campaign and Judean invasion that does not match his historical death in Persia.</p>',
    "41": '<p><strong>The Beautiful Land</strong> = Judea (see 11:16). Edom, Moab, and the leaders of Ammon escape — historically, these Transjordanian nations had various accommodations with Antiochus IV and the Seleucid power. If read eschatologically, they represent nations that receive temporary reprieve at the end of the age. The specific geography is striking: the prediction explicitly names three peoples east of the Jordan who are not conquered.</p>',
    "42": '<p>Egypt does not escape — "he will extend his power over many countries" including Egypt. The contrast with vv.25-30 (where Antiochus IV reached Egypt but was expelled by Rome) reinforces the sense that vv.40-45 describe a different scenario than the 168 BCE campaign.</p>',
    "43": '<p><strong>Treasures of gold and silver</strong> with Libya and Cush "at his steps" — control of Egypt\'s wealth and the submission of the North African nations. This level of Egyptian domination exceeds what Antiochus IV historically achieved. Libya (H3864 <em>Luvim</em>) and Cush (H3568, Ethiopia/Sudan) represent the western and southern extent of the Ptolemaic sphere of influence.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"Reports from the east and the north will alarm him" — something draws the king away from his Egyptian campaign, and he responds with extreme violence. Historically, Antiochus IV\'s last campaign was eastward (into Persia/Elymais), not from the east northward. This verse\'s geography is one of the textual details that makes simple identification with Antiochus IV\'s historical career difficult.</p>',
    "45": '<p><strong>Royal tents between the sea and the beautiful holy mountain</strong> = the Mediterranean coast and Mount Zion/Jerusalem — this geographic staging is the final position of the eschatological adversary before his end. <strong>Yet he will come to his end, and no one will help him</strong> — the abrupt divine termination of the power that seemed unstoppable. Antiochus IV died at Tabae (Persia, 164 BCE), not in Palestine; if this verse is read of him, it represents unfulfilled prediction requiring reinterpretation; if read eschatologically, it describes the final end of the end-time adversary. The connection to Dan 12:1-2 is immediate: after this end, "Michael will arise" and the resurrection occurs.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'daniel')
    merge_comm(existing, DANIEL)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'daniel', existing)
    print('Daniel 9-11 mkt-context commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
